Phase 6 Part 9 - Final QA: real typecheck run against the actual source

Discovery: this sandbox has no npm registry access (confirmed again, same
as every earlier phase), so no third-party package types (@types/node,
@types/react, express, pg, zod, react, react-router-dom, etc.) are
installed in either backend/node_modules or frontend/node_modules.
HOWEVER, a real TypeScript compiler (v6.0.3) and tsx (v4.22.4) ARE
present globally at /usr/local/lib/node_modules_global/bin/ (not on PATH
by default) -- discovered and used for the first time in this session
during Part 9. This made two previously-impossible checks possible for
real: an actual `tsc --noEmit` run, and an actual `node --test` run of
every real test file (see phase6-part9-full-test-suite-run.log).

tsc --noEmit was run with one non-functional accommodation: a throwaway
config extending the real tsconfig.json/tsconfig.app.json with
"ignoreDeprecations": "6.0" added, ONLY to stop TS 6.0.3 from refusing to
even start over "moduleResolution: node"/"baseUrl" being marked
deprecated-in-a-future-major-version -- this flag changes no compiled
output and was never added to the real committed tsconfig files (which
target the project's actual pinned `typescript: ^5.5.4`).

Backend: 313 errors on first run. Manually triaged every one. 311 were
directly attributable to a missing npm package (Cannot find module
'express'/'pg'/'zod'/'dotenv'/etc, Cannot find name 'process'/'Buffer'/
'console'/'fetch'/'URL' from missing @types/node, ZodError/Multer/etc
losing their real shape without their type packages) -- confirmed
resolvable purely by installing real dependencies, not real code bugs.
2 were real: PropertyDetailDTO.ts imported PropertyLocation and
PropertyImage but never used either (both fields are defined as inline
object literal types instead) -- FIXED by removing the two unused
imports. Re-ran after the fix: 311 errors (down from 313 by exactly 2),
confirming the fix and no regression. Full test suite re-run after the
fix: still 184/184 passing.

A separate, security-motivated fix made later in this same Part 9 pass
(metrics.routes.ts's bearer-token check used `!==` instead of this
codebase's established timingSafeEqual pattern -- see
phase6-part9-security-audit.log) added 3 new "Cannot find name
'Buffer'/'node:crypto'" entries to this same missing-@types/node bucket
(314 total after that fix) -- confirmed via a targeted re-run that these
3 are the same environmental cascade as everything else in this
category, not new real bugs.

Frontend: 2154 errors on first run, essentially all attributable to
@types/react/@types/react-dom/vite/react-router-dom being uninstalled
(1937 alone were "JSX element implicitly has type any because no
interface JSX.IntrinsicElements exists" -- the single most common
cascade from missing @types/react). Manually triaged every distinct
error code (TS7026, TS7006, TS2307, TS2875, TS2322, TS7031, TS2503,
TS2882, TS2345, TS2339) rather than assuming the count meant nothing was
worth checking. One real, environment-independent bug found:
src/api/admin.ts's searchProperties() passed a named-interface-typed
`filters: AdminPropertySearchFilters` variable directly into a
Record<string, ...>-typed parameter, which TypeScript's structural
index-signature check rejects for named interfaces (it accepts fresh
object literals more leniently) -- this is a real TS rule that applies
under the project's own pinned TypeScript version too, not a
sandbox-only quirk. FIXED by spreading into a fresh literal:
`{ ...filters }`. Re-ran after the fix: 2153 errors (down from 2154 by
exactly 1), confirming the fix and no regression.

Every other error code was manually reviewed and confirmed as a cascade
from a missing package (e.g. AdminAnalyticsRepository.ts's "unknown"-typed
reduce() and ImageUploadManager.tsx's "unknown[] not assignable to
File[]" both stem from generic type parameters on methods whose
declaring class comes from an unresolvable "pg"/DOM-lib-via-@types/react
import; the ~9 "key" prop TS2322 errors across page components are
React's own special-cased `key` prop not being excluded from prop
checking without @types/react's JSX.LibraryManagedAttributes machinery).
None of these were "fixed" since doing so would mean changing correct
code to work around an absent dependency, which would not match how the
project's own pinned TypeScript version behaves once real npm install
has run.

Recommendation before a real production build: run `npm install` for
real in both backend/ and frontend/ (see docs/phase-6-part6-cicd.md's
lockfile gap note) and re-run `tsc --noEmit` in each -- with real
packages installed, expect the error count to drop to at or near zero
given the above triage.
